1. 2. cum. In some instanees an ablative of manner, not qualified by an adjective or genitive dependent on it, may be used with or without ‘ cum.' Thus we can say ‘ clamore’ or ‘cum clamore '; ‘silentio ' or ‘ cum silentio! But as a rule ‘ cum ' should be used when the ablative . is unqualified. ‘ Cum dolore‚' ‘ cum fide,‘ ⁶ cum cura,' are better than ‘dolore,’ ‘fide‚’ ‘cura‚' respectively. l. 4. parricidio. Used of any unnatural murder. Perseus had in· duced his father Philip to poison his elder brother Demetrius as being too Roman in his tendencies. Philip dying soon afterwards, Livy hints by the words ‘mors peropportuna Perseo' that he too died of foul play.
